{"parse":{"title":"Light clay","pageid":18401357,"revid":823137767,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Light_clay_infill.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Light_clay_infill.JPG/220px-Light_clay_infill.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Light_clay_infill.JPG/330px-Light_clay_infill.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Light_clay_infill.JPG/440px-Light_clay_infill.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"2048\" data-file-height=\"1536\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Light_clay_infill.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Example use of light clay within a timber frame before rendering</div></div></div><p><b>Light clay</b> (also <b>light straw clay</b>, <b>light clay straw</b>, <b>slipstraw</b>) is a natural building material used to infill between a wooden frame in a <a href=\"/wiki/Timber_framing\" title=\"Timber framing\">timber framed</a> building using a combination of <a href=\"/wiki/Clay\" title=\"Clay\">clay</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Straw\" title=\"Straw\">straw</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Woodchips\" title=\"Woodchips\">woodchips</a> or some other lighter material.\n</p><div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Usage\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Usage</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Light_clay&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>A mixture of clay and straw was used as an infill material for <a href=\"/wiki/Timber_framing\" title=\"Timber framing\">timber framed</a> building from at least the 12th century in Germany and elsewhere in Europe.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Renewed interest in traditional building methods developed from the 1980s after which various <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_building\" title=\"Natural building\">natural building</a> architects and builders started promoting the use of light clay.<sup id=\"cite_ref-art_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-art-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Usage\">Usage</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Light_clay&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Usage\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Light_clay_mix.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Light_clay_mix.JPG/220px-Light_clay_mix.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Light_clay_mix.JPG/330px-Light_clay_mix.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Light_clay_mix.JPG/440px-Light_clay_mix.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"2048\" data-file-height=\"1536\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Light_clay_mix.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Light clay mixture consisting of clay, water and straw before application</div></div></div>\n<p>Local clay, often local subsoil, is mixed into a slurry with water and then combined with straw or wood chip or other similar material. Wood chips can vary in size from <a href=\"/wiki/Sawdust\" title=\"Sawdust\">sawdust</a> to chip 5cm in diameter.<sup id=\"cite_ref-art_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-art-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The ratio of clay to other ingredients can be adapted to either increase thermal mass or insulation properties.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The mixture is provided with additional structural strength using <a href=\"/wiki/Wattle_and_daub\" title=\"Wattle and daub\">wattles</a>. When used externally it can be protected with a <a href=\"/wiki/Lime_render\" title=\"Lime render\">Lime render</a> or a clay render.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Light_clay&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Adobe\" title=\"Adobe\">Adobe</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Cob_(material)\" title=\"Cob (material)\">Cob</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Wattle_and_daub\" title=\"Wattle and daub\">Wattle and daub</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Wychert\" title=\"Wychert\">Wychert</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Light_clay&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.networkearth.org/naturalbuilding/clay.html\">\"An Introduction to Traditional and Modern German Clay Building\"</a>. <q>Building with clay has a long tradition in Germany and other European countries. Framed structures (half-timbered houses) from the 12th century, filled with a mixture of clay and straw fibers, still exist.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=An+Introduction+to+Traditional+and+Modern+German+Clay+Building&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.networkearth.org%2Fnaturalbuilding%2Fclay.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight+clay\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-art-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-art_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-art_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=054_i8KdcCAC&amp;pg=PA167&amp;lpg=PA167&amp;dq=%22light+clay%22+natural&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=4VzMTspw_L&amp;sig=QrHVmnQrZZJNMYHs0fG7N6Lr6K8&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=Izy8TaLtJ5CwhQetk8HRBQ&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=9&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CFoQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&amp;q=%22light%20clay%22%20natural&